It cannot be said that we have any news here, of much moment. We live quite quietly among a small circle of people, who see us from time to time, not so often as usual in the bitter weather; I do not go out
much to dinner or soirees (evening-parties); Jane does not go out at all, not even in the day-time, and accordingly has grown very impatient for mild weather again. However, she takes really handsomely to her in-doors life; and has not been better, I think, these good many winters: she (and you and all weakly people) must be especially careful about this spring season, the most insidious and injurious of all. We are generally alone in the evenings, tranquil over our books and papers; what visitors and visiting we have are in the middle of the day.On 16 Feb. the Carlyles had several visitors. On returning from a walk TC found that Thomas Spedding had called and “Cavaignac with two bottles of champagne—was come to dine with us! Smiles; from the teeth outwards: but the purpose was kind, was welcome. Dinner not yet served, arrives Mrs John Sterling with the children in a Neat-fly. Talkee-talkee; which our maid benevolently stopt by entering with the soup,—‘like a bolt out of the blue.’ Dinner done, tant bien que mal [on balance, quite well], and C. and I smoking up stairs, arrives to tea good Thomas Erskine the Christian-Evidence; Cavaignac and he to feed together like the lion and the lamb! It passed pacifically; E. went away before ten, C. not till after el[e]ven” (Journal, 17 Feb.). With my will I would go out nowhere to visit in the evening; it never fails to do me more or less harm: but here there is no other way of carrying on intercourse with several sorts of people whom one likes otherwise to see. My most remarkable evening-party for a great while was one lately at no smaller a personage’s than—who think you?—the Chancellor of the Exchequer’s!Thomas Spring Rice (1790–1866), Whig politician; M.P. for Limerick 1820–32, for Cambridge 1832–39; chancellor of the exchequer under Melbourne, 1835–39; comptroller of exchequer and 1st Baron Monteagle, 1839. His second wife, m. 1841, Mary Anne Marshall (1800–89), was the da. of John Marshall, later TC’s friend, and sister-in-law of Spring Rice’s two eldest das. I went for the curiosity, for the honour of the thing. They invited me a second time; but I was absent and did not go. The invitation being now on my table, I think I will send it you, as a strange thing enough. I could not help thinking, Here is the man that disposes annually of the whole revenue of England; and here is another man who has hardly enough of cash to buy potatoes and onions for himself: Fortune has for the time made these two tenants of one drawing-room. The case, I believe, is this: Miss Spring Rice,Mary Alicia Pery Spring Rice (1812–75), maid of honor to Victoria, m., 1841, James Garth Marshall (1802–73), third son of John Marshall. the Chancellor of the Exchequer’s eldest daughter, a very beautiful and rather intelligent young woman, was one of my German hearers last year, and took a fancy for my notability; so her mother the Lady TheodosiaLady Theodosia, b. Pery (1787–1839), second da. of 1st Earl of Limerick, m. 1811. was obliged to be “at home” for me. The people were very kind; Spring Rice himself a substantial goodhumoured shifty-looking man of fifty: the rooms were genial with heat, and light as the sun at noon;
there were high dames and “distinguished males,”Cf. “distinguished females”; coterie speech. simmering about like people in the press of a June-Fair: the whole thing went off very well; and I returned about one in the morning with a headache that served me for more than a day after. “It will help your Lectures,” Jane said. May be so; but in the meantime it has quite hindered my natural sleep and composure.TC noted in his Journal, 14 Feb.: “My notablest social performance or endurance, this winter … a soiree of Spring Rice Chancellor of the Exchequer’s. … ‘Most happy to make your acquaintance,’ and you possessor in the Earth of some four score pounds sterling,—the sum-total that of your properties, prospects, and pecuniary kingdom under the sun! … It was a brilliant-looking thing; all very polite; marchioness &c, ‘with feelings exactly like ours’ (as my dear Mother said of the Foreign persons in W. Meister): it shook my nerves much, so late were the hours for one thing; but I thought it might be useful, as Jane did; and so went. Soirees in general are a nullity and mockery to me.” ——— I had another Letter from Emerson the American friend, sent by a person he was introducing to me:Charles Summer (1811–74), U.S. sen. 1851–74, and a leading congressional opponent of slavery; at this time a lawyer in Boston, travelling in Europe for two years. He had sent the letter on from Paris; see TC to RWE, 16 March16 March. by this it appears that the F. Revolution is reprinted in New England by Emerson’s care, and that I am to have some money out of it, no less!For Emerson’s letter of 2 Nov. 1837, see TC to JAC, 1 Feb. The Articles are going on, I suppose, on the same principle. American money for my writings will be curious to get; and welcome, as all money is. As for Fraser he continues sick, tho’ a little less dangerously so than before; his projects of printing and reprinting are quite blown by for the present.

Monday morning.— Dear Wifie, one word more before we go this morning. I have been awake since six (yet dozing again, and not bathing);
in spite of the hours &c, I feel decidedly in an improved and improving way. We are to be off to Leslie Village,Nine mi. NW of Kirkcaldy. John Fergus & Co., bleachers and flax-spinners, founded 1828, was at Prinlaws, immediately W of Leslie. John and I, at eleven o’clock, that is in half an hour. Brief therefore!— Yesterday afternoon we had the Surgeon, one Philp to dinner, a simple scrub-headed, pacific man.Kirkcaldy had several surgeons, none called Philp. My foot had grown decidedly and altogether unaccountably lame: Philp suggested that probably I had been bit in bathing by a medusa or sea-nettle; I think it is so, for today it feels greatly mended, and I halt no more. This morning JardineJames Jardine (see 1:153TC to MAC, 17 Dec. 1818) of 18 Queen St., Edinburgh, had been born in Applegarth, Dumfriesshire. the Edinr Engineer stept in to breakfast: a hard sarcastic old fellow, with a large white broadbrimmed hat; perfect in his Annandale dialect to a degree that leaves even me behind: we did very well he and I. On Wednesday they say Mrs James StewartEleanor Maria Anna Stuart, b. Mowbray (d. 1868), from Cockairnie, Fife; m. 1802. and perhaps Mr James (American Stewart)James Stuart (1775–1849), W.S. 1798; see 2:139TC to AC, 29 June 1822, and 6:372–73TC to AC, 18 April 1833. are coming; which shall be well. I went to tea with Mrs SwanMargaret Hutchison Swan; see 1:143TC to RM, 6 Nov. 1818. She lived at 201 High St.; “a tall, good-looking, and intelligent lady, hospitable, and a good conversationalist in her own house, but holding somewhat aloof from ladies of her station in the town” (L. Macbean, Patrick Don Swan [Kirkcaldy, 1893] 6). last night, having in despair sent a Note that I would do it and got her sanction: she was in deep widow-weeds, very lugubrious; but the two ladsTwo of the four surviving brothers—Patrick, Thomas (d. 1840), William (d. 1859), or Alexander (d. 1867)—who all worked in Swan Brothers, shippers and spinners. and I helped the matter out. I suppose I must go back and dine some day. Happily Mrs MartinMargaret Martin (d. 1846), da. of Andrew Walker, farmer, Carslogie; m., 1796, John Martin, minister at Kirkcaldy from 1807 till his death in 1837 (see 9:313TC to JAC, 21 Sept. 1837). is at present in London. The sculduddery process still goes on; men think the minister is innocent, but that the wife is doubly and trebly guilty.Presumably referring not to the Martins, the Rev. John having “served his day and generation with great acceptance and esteem” (John Campbell, Church and Parish of Kirkcaldy [Kirkcaldy, 1904] 212), but to their da. Isabella Irving and her influence on Edward Irving’s religious ideas and practice before his death, 1834; cf. 8:53TC to JAC, 16 Feb. 1835, and 8:56TC to MAC, 17 Feb. 1835 for JWC’s and TC’s earlier comments on Isabella. Ach Gott! But whither do I run?— Some days ago I went along to the Port Brae with Ellen’sHelen Mitchell. letter, Miss Fergus conducting me. We saw Ellen’s sister, and spoke a while with her: a very active, discreet, sonsy [cheerful] little woman, who seemed right glad to see us, and hear the news we brought. She
was well and her husband, and indeed all Ellen’s kindred; her two brothers here (I think she said) even now. The husband’s business, like all business, has been “slack” for some months, but they seemed to be in good heart; his shop, in which we sat while there, was respectably filled with mahogany cabinet-work &c, and had a prosperous enough air.There was a cabinet maker and upholsterer, Andrew Black, on East Port, but none is listed on Port Brae. They promised to write, but accused Ellen of being negligent herself. This is all: every one well, and affectionate to the absent. I did not promise to call again, but could do it if your Bank Street Letter had an order to that effect.
